data.content:
Here are the migration issues for each snippet:

## Form1.cs â€” `ContextMenu`/`MenuItem` removed

These legacy types are **removed in .NET 10** (they were error-obsoleted via `WFDEV009`/`WFDEV010` in .NET 9). Replace with the modern equivalents:

```csharp
var menu = new ContextMenuStrip();
menu.Items.Add(new ToolStripMenuItem("Open", image: null, OnOpen));
```

## ImageProcessor.cs â€” Exception type changed

GDI+ historically threw `OutOfMemoryException` for invalid/corrupt images. In .NET 10, this now throws **`ArgumentException`** instead. Your `catch (OutOfMemoryException)` will miss it:

```csharp
try
{
    using var bmp = new Bitmap(path);
    bmp.SetResolution(300, 300);
}
catch (ArgumentException ex)
{
    logger.LogError(ex, "Invalid image format");
}
```

## MainWindow.xaml â€” No code changes needed, but watch for runtime issues

The empty `<Grid.ColumnDefinitions/>` and `<Grid.RowDefinitions/>` are harmless but unnecessary. The `DynamicResource MissingKey` reference silently resolves to `null` at runtime â€” .NET 10 WPF now **logs diagnostic warnings** for missing resource keys, so expect new noise in debug output. Define the key or switch to `FallbackValue`:

```xml
<TextBlock Text="{DynamicResource MissingKey, FallbackValue='N/A'}" />
```

## Additional notes from your project context

- **StatusStrip**: .NET 10 changes the default `ToolStripRenderMode` from `ManagerRenderMode` to `System`, altering appearance. Explicitly set `statusStrip.RenderMode = ToolStripRenderMode.Professional` to preserve the look.
- **TreeView checkboxes**: The `AfterCheck` event behavior changed â€” it now fires **once** per programmatic check change instead of potentially double-firing. Verify any toggle logic that compensated for the old behavior.
